Overview

On Day 5, I upgraded the project from manually managing containers to a fully orchestrated multi-container architecture using Docker Compose.

Previously:

Node.js container was started manually
Redis container was started separately
Networking and configuration required manual setup

With Docker Compose, the entire infrastructure can now be started using a single command:

docker-compose up

This marks an important transition toward production-style DevOps workflows.

🎯 Day 5 Objectives

The main goals of Day 5 were:

Automate multi-container startup
Simplify infrastructure management
Enable service-to-service communication
Use environment variables for configuration
Create a cleaner and scalable development workflow
🧠 What is Docker Compose?

Docker Compose is a tool used to define and manage multi-container Docker applications.

Instead of manually running multiple containers, Compose allows all services to be managed through a single YAML configuration file.

Benefits include:

Easier orchestration
Automatic networking
Simplified deployment
Consistent environments
