🛠️ What I Implemented
1️⃣ Created docker-compose.yml

Defined multiple services:

Node.js application
Redis database

Configuration included:

Container names
Port mappings
Environment variables
Service dependencies

Example:

version: '3'

services:

  app:
    build: .
    container_name: realtime-app

    ports:
      - "3000:3000"

    depends_on:
      - redis

    environment:
      REDIS_URL: redis://redis:6379

  redis:
    image: redis
    container_name: redis-server
2️⃣ Added Environment Variable Configuration

Updated Redis connection in server.js.

Before:

url: "redis://localhost:6379"

After:

url: process.env.REDIS_URL

This made the application portable across:

Local environments
Docker environments
Production systems
3️⃣ Automatic Service Networking

Docker Compose automatically created:

Shared network
Internal DNS resolution

This allowed the app container to connect to Redis using:

redis://redis:6379

instead of localhost.

4️⃣ Container Orchestration

Successfully orchestrated:

Redis container
Node.js application container

using a single command:

docker-compose up --build
🧱 Challenges Faced
🔹 Port Conflict Issues

Encountered:

Bind for 0.0.0.0:6379 failed: port is already allocated
Cause

Old Redis containers were still running.

Solution
Removed old containers
Cleaned Docker environment
Avoided unnecessary Redis port exposure
🔹 Container Name Conflicts

Encountered:

container name already in use
Solution

Removed existing containers before rebuilding.

🔹 Event Name Mismatch

Frontend initially used old socket event names.

Fixed By

Updating all layers to use:

agent:update
agent:subscribe
🔹 Agent ID Mismatch

Frontend subscribed to:

agent1

while simulator emitted:

agent_1
Solution

Ensured consistent naming across:

frontend
simulator
backend
